🌐 1. What is $_GET?

$_GET is used when data is sent in the URL.
Example URL:
example.com/page.php?name=John&age=22

Then in PHP:
echo $_GET['name'];  // John
echo $_GET['age'];   // 22

Key points:
✔ Data appears in URL
✔ Easy to test manually
✔ Not secure for passwords
✔ Good for filters, searching, navigation

🌐 2. What is $_POST?
$_POST receives data sent from a form (body of the request), not visible in the URL.

Example form:
<form method="POST">
    <input type="text" name="username">
    <input type="submit">
</form>
In PHP:
echo $_POST['username'];
Key points:
✔ Data is NOT visible in URL
✔ More secure
✔ Used for login, forms, sensitive data
✔ Can send large amounts of data

🌐 3. What is $_REQUEST?
$_REQUEST = combines GET + POST + COOKIE
If you write:
echo $_REQUEST['username'];
It will search:
POST data
GET data
Cookies

Most developers avoid using it because:
It’s unclear where the data comes from
Can create bugs or security issues

🌐 4. What is $_SERVER?
$_SERVER contains information about the server and the request, such as:
Useful values:
$_SERVER['REMOTE_ADDR'];  // User's IP
$_SERVER['HTTP_USER_AGENT']; // Browser info
$_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'];  // GET or POST
$_SERVER['REQUEST_URI'];  // URL path
$_SERVER['SERVER_NAME'];  // Domain name
$_SERVER['HTTP_HOST'];    // Host header
Example:
echo $_SERVER['REMOTE_ADDR'];
This prints the visitor’s IP address.

🌐 5. What is a session? ($_SESSION)
Sessions store temporary data for each user on the server.
Example uses:
Login systems
Shopping cart
Keeping user data between pages
Basic usage:
session_start();
$_SESSION['username'] = "Anna";

On another page:
session_start();
echo $_SESSION['username']; // Anna

🌐 6. What is a cookie? ($_COOKIE)
Cookies store small data on the user's browser, not on the server.
Example:
setcookie("theme", "dark", time()+3600); // 1 hour

Later:
echo $_COOKIE['theme']; // dark

Cookies are used for:
Remembering preferences (theme, language)
Tracking logins
Analytics

🌐 7. Difference between GET and POST
Feature	GET	POST
Data location	URL	Request body
Visible in address bar	Yes	No
Data size	Small	Large
Safe for passwords	❌ No	✔ Yes
Typical use	Search, filters, links	Forms, login, uploads
🌐 8. What is a query string?

?key=value&key2=value2

Part of the URL after ?.
Everything after it is data for the server.

Example:

site.com/page.php?color=red&size=large


PHP gets it using $_GET.

🌐 9. What is a form submission?

An HTML form sends data to the server.

Example:

<form action="submit.php" method="POST">
    <input type="text" name="email">
    <button>Send</button>
</form>


Then in submit.php:

echo $_POST['email'];

🌐 10. What is a request method?

$_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] shows whether the browser used GET or POST.

Example:

if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    echo "Form submitted!";
}

✔️ Summary Table
Term	Meaning	Example
GET	Data in URL	$_GET['id']
POST	Data sent from form	$_POST['email']
REQUEST	GET + POST + COOKIE	$_REQUEST['x']
SERVER	Server & request info	$_SERVER['REMOTE_ADDR']
SESSION	User data stored on server	$_SESSION['user']
COOKIE	User data stored in browser	$_COOKIE['theme']


